<br>
Think of utility as flexibility.  <br>
<br>
In baseball a 'utility' player is someone that can play multiple positions without a loss of functionality to the group.  So a manager can slap a shortstop onto second base, and not lose defense or offense.<br>
<br>
In EQ, a warrior has no utility.  He can't play multiple positions without costing a group some effectiveness.  <br>
<br>
If the warrior is put in the pulling role without sometimes having to be pulled back as a corpse.<br>
<br>
If he is put into the second assist role, then yes, he's only as good as his sword (can't use taunt, not taking the main damage).  <br>
<br>
And of course he can't do anything else (healer, whatever).<br>
<br>
I'll leave the other people to argue about who is balanced with what.  But there's no denying the fact that warriors can only really do one thing decently well.  And that's take damage.<br>
<br>
