<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
As to the monk Vs Warrior comparison, as I pointed out on the FoH board:<br>
<br>
 Assuming monk avoidance is the same as warrior (misses) and that dodge and riposte are the same, monks take an addition 16% or so less damage per hit thanks to BLock vs parry. Block goes off about 12% last time I checked (been several months) and parry around 4%. Given a warrior or monk with CA3 wboth classes avoid (miss/block/dodge/riposte/parry) around 50% of all attacks. The addition 8% of avoided attacks out of 50% attacks that land is about a 16% reduction in damage taken.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I dont see how you came to this figure of 16% from your own discussion.<br>
<br>
Using your starting data a simple scenario would be:<br>
<br>
Given an npc hits both a monk and a warrior 200 times and for simplicity's sake the same amount each time.<br>
<br>
After applying your estimated avoidance of 50% we are left with 100 hits for each.<br>
<br>
For the 100 hits that get through subtract those avoided by block for the monk and parry for the warrior.<br>
<br>
You are left with 88 hits on the monk, and 96 hits on the warrior.<br>
<br>
Damage taken over this period,<br>
<br>
relative to the monk, the warrior takes 8.3% more damage<br>
<br>
relative to the warrior, the monk takes 9% less damage.<br>
<br>
All of this is with the implicit assumption that during this time the warrior and the monk are being hit for the same average damage. Now it might be said to be true for highend raid encounters, and probably also for highlevel well equiped players in older zones, but not necessarily in all situations of play. Certainly as soon as a warrior uses evasive or defensive this situation is different.<br>
<br>
As much as warriors try to throw away those two disciplines when arguing this point, the fact remains they exist and are often used in difficult encounters. They are as much a part of the warrior arsenal as mend and feign death for the monk.<br>
<br>
Granted you can succeed on a lot of end game encounters without using defensive or evasive simply by increasing the rate of the heal rotation. However often times the same can be said of monks pulling, its certainly not essential for us to pull many of the things we do.<br>
